				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The level I intended at that point was &quot;what&quot; the transistor does (when used as an on/off switch, as is usually the case in digital electronics), not &quot;how&quot; it does it. For what it's worth, I wrote that while I still had a very vague idea of the physics behind transistors (it's slightly better now, but still very basic). I'm a top-down kind of guy, but other people's brains might work differently. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_confused.gif" alt=":?" title="Confused" /><br /><br />I found this video helpful for understanding &quot;how&quot; (NMOS) transistors work: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IcrBqCFLHIY">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IcrBqCFLHIY</a><!-- m -->. Understanding it at that level is not essential for reading most of the circuitry in the Visual * simulators though.<br /><br />Do you think it would be helpful to move the video to an earlier point in the tutorial? Any other suggestions?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">1)  What determines whether or not the input polysilicon is high?<br /></div><br /><br />The input polysilicon is high if it is connected to a power source and the current from that power source doesn't go to ground. A more electronicy way of saying that is that the voltage on the gate (input polysilicon) must be pulled to VCC rather than to ground. Here's two trivial (and somewhat pointless) examples:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; VCC<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />VCC------&#91;gate&#93;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(gate is always high (always conducts current), A will be powered/pulled to VCC)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A<br /><br /><br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; VCC<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />GND------&#91;gate&#93;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(gate is always low (never conducts current), A will _not_ be powered/pulled to VCC)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A<br /></div><br /><br />Whether a gate is high or low could also be influenced by other gates:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />VCC-------+-------&#91;gate B&#93;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp;...---&#91;gate A&#93;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;GND&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br /></div><br /><br />In the above case, gate A being high means that gate B will be low (current will to ground instead of to gate B), and vice versa. This is the same situation as for the inverter, if you assume the output in that figure goes to gate B.<br /><br />I hope that helps. Maybe the tutorial could be clearer on what being &quot;high&quot; means for a node.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">2)  How does the input polysilicon here affect the output polysilicon when they don't touch?  I assume the current flows through the other diffusion areas, but how?  What determines which diffusion area receives current and when?<br /></div><br /><br />Not sure if I'm getting the question. If the poly doesn't touch the diffusion, then you won't have a transistor, and no current will ever flow between between. I realize that probably isn't what you mean though, so maybe you can clarify. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />Edit: Shouldn't have said &quot;between them&quot;, as current never flows from the gate to the source/drain. What I meant is that current never flows across &quot;gaps&quot; if areas don't touch at all.<br /><br />The actual structure of transistors is like in the video I posted, so the 2D display is a bit of an abstraction. Whenever you have a polysilicon strip squished between areas of diffusion, you can be pretty sure there's a transistor there though (and you can click on it to see if it gets highlighted if you want to be extra sure).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

