						<div class="postbody">Thanks for the reply, ulfalizer.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; VCC<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />GND------&#91;gate&#93;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(gate is always low (never conducts current), A will _not_ be powered/pulled to VCC)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;|<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A<br /></div><br /><br />I'm still a little confused.  The wiki mentions:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">wiki wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">When a piece of polysilicon is sandwiched between two areas of diffusion, it acts as a gate, only letting current through when the polysilicon is powered (or, equivalently, on, conducting, high, or 1).</div><br /><br />So... in this example... for the current to reach GND from VCC in this example... wouldn't the gate have to be high in order to allow current to pass through it?  It seems to me if the gate is low, the current wouldn't go anywhere and would be trapped at the VCC.  Doesn't it have to go <strong>through</strong> the gate to reach GND?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Not sure if I'm getting the question.</div><br /><br />It's very likely the question doesn't make sense.  Perhaps I should focus on understanding the first question before I try to ask a 2nd  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /></div>

