			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So... in this example... for the current to reach GND from VCC in this example... wouldn't the gate have to be high in order to allow current to pass through it?</div><br /><br />The current from the wire connected to VCC in that drawing will never go to the wire connected to GND. The voltage on the gate only controls whether or not it lets current through (whether or not it's conductive) - you never get current going from the &quot;source/drain wires&quot; onto the &quot;gate wire&quot; or vice versa.<br /><br />To put it another way, current will never flow from A to B or from C to B (or vice versa) in the figure below:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />B-----&#91;gate&#93;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; C<br /></div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It seems to me if the gate is low, the current wouldn't go anywhere and would be trapped at the VCC.</div><br /><br />That's exactly how it works. Think of the gate as an actual gate. When it's high/open, it lets current through (it is conductive). When it's low/closed, it blocks current (not conductive). (I've been discouraged from using the open/closed terminology for gates though, as open/closed have the opposite meaning for switches.)<br /><br />It's a bit of a balancing act to talk about currents instead of voltages though. On the one hand, I find currents easier to think about than voltages, but on the other hand, you often don't have any actual current flowing in the steady state (the state after things have &quot;settled down&quot; after e.g. a clock tick). In the example above where the gate is connected to VCC, the current is &quot;trapped&quot; in the gate and doesn't flow, but the condition for the gate to be high isn't that current flows in it - it's just that the voltage on the gate is at VCC.<br /><br />The way I visualize it is that the gate is high if you have current &quot;pushing into it&quot; (though not flowing, since it doesn't have anywhere to go).<br /><br />Edit: As a side note, one reason NMOS tends to waste more power compared to CMOS is that you often have an (actual) current flowing in the steady state for NMOS. For example, if the input to the inverter is high, then you have a current going from VCC to ground even in the steady state.</div>

