				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">oohh.. okay, so current could still go A&lt;-&gt;C  just not to B.<br /><br />Thanks for bearing with me.  I'm really trying to wrap my head around this.<br /><br />Coming back to the inversion example... ASCII-ified:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; XXXXX....<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; X<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; X <br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; XXXXXX<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; XXXX&nbsp; &nbsp;Q&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;N<br />VCC-XXXX-DIFFUSE-N-GND<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; XXXX&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;N <br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;N<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.<br /></div><br /><br />Here's the sense I could make out of how it works.  Perhaps you could point out the flaws in my understanding?<br /><br />1)  Current originates at VCC<br />2)  current travels from VCC to DIFFUSE (how?  wouldn't it depend on 'X' gate?)<br />3)  if 'N' gate is high, current goes from DIFFUSE to GND, and therefore does not go to X, leaving X low.<br />4)  if 'N' gate is low, current goes from DIFFUSE to X (through that second 'Q' joining?) thereby forcing X high.</div><br /><br />Note that the 'X' gate has a hook in it, which means it's one of the &quot;special&quot; transistors used as resistors on power sources (<!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Visual_circuit_tutorial#Power_sources">http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Visu ... er_sources</a><!-- m -->). Ignoring that resistor (which is just there to limit the current that can flow), you get the following diagram:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; /-----...(output)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |&nbsp; &nbsp;g<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;VCC----+---a---GND<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; t<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; e<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; |<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(input)<br /></div><br /><br />To be perfectly honest, I'm not sure exactly how the depletion-mode transistors (the hooked ones on power sources) work, but the only thing that's important to know about them when starting out is that they act as resistors on power sources. The diagram above is how the simulator views the circuit - it doesn't model the depletion-mode transistor as a separate transistor.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

